            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The text is only recorded by Octavius Caietanus (1566-1620) in his 'Isagoge ad historiam sacram siculam' (published posthumously in 1707), where he simply describes it as a 'tabella mamorea Syracusis reperta graeco idiomate', which he renders in Latin. 'Amphilobi' clearly refers to an 'amphipolos'. It clearly bears close similarity to the inscriptions for Anna and the Paides from Buscemi (cf. ISic002997 or 002999), and given that and the Latin names, is probably of the early first century CE.</p>
                    <!--A Greek text reconstructed from a Latin translation. cf. SEG 42.0825-0836; Tusa discusses in context of info on amphipoloi. Inscr. opens with the eponymous priest, and then the amphipolis, but the Latin is garbled, making the Grk. reconstruction diff, It is suggested by Manganaro, in Rupes Loquentes, p.455-87 at 472 with n.40, that this inscr. might refer to the cult of Anna and the Paides, rather than to Dea Syria (NB I would both agree and go further, and suggest that line one 'dea syria' is actually a misconstrual of syrakousai, and that the overall form is almost identical to e.g. ISic2997 or 2999. Cf. the 5 inscrs. from Buscemi to Anna and the Paides, which also record amphipolis at Syracuse, AD 35 (Wilson, p.280; cf. Pugliese Carratelli, PdP 6 (1951), p.68-75. Roger suggests it belongs between C1 BC and 50 AD.  cf. ASNP 1981, p.1069ff for 2 oracle inscrs. from Akrai region with mentions of Nymphs and Paides. SGDI 5256 in the notes observes that this appears to refer to the amphipolis of the paides.-->
            </div>
